x4freetext: CYCLONE110
Different projectile energies on target were obtained
by changing the primary energy of the beam and by
employing Mylar degraders of 25 and 50mu-m in thickness
The uranium target consisted of a UF4 layer,
500+-50 mu-g/cm2 in total, deposited on a thin carbon
foil (30mu-g/cm2)
The two heavy fragments emitted in the
fission decay were detected in an array of forty
50 x 50 mm2 silicon detectors. The detectors were
arranged on the inner faces of two cubes, four on each
face, completely surrounding the target.
The identification of the fission fragments was
based on their energy and on the geometry of the
emission.
Statistical error
the overall systematic uncertainty (from the
total beam irradiation, target thickness, and
efficiency measurement) is estimated to be around 17%.
To obtain the angular distributions, the detected
yields were corrected for the detection efficiency of
each ring in the corresponding angular region, as
measured using the calibrated a source (thus using the
approximation of a uniform distribution of the light
charged particles in each ring).
Data received from Dr. R.Raabe
Entry approved by Dr. R.Raabe

x4freetext: Each point is the integral cross section on the angular
range covered by each of the six detector rings
Angular distributions of the light charged particles
detected in coincidence with fission events.
Thus these are Incomplete Fusion or Direct Reaction
cross section (lower limits due to the coincident
fission requirement).
Small quantities of radioactive 7Be (T1/2 = 53 d) were
obtained by a (p,n) reaction on the 7Li content of a
LiF target, irradiated by the 30 MeV proton beam of
the CYCLONE30 cyclotron.
